Morality, like most concepts in a given society are historical terms. The fact that the communist program arises from the material conditions of capitalism and not of a place of morality doesn't mean that individuals (communists or not) can be unaffected by the existing traditions of the current society.

Which is why i detach my personal morals from this analysis. Author: stayflyyyy
Content:
the Cultural Revolution, or more properly the Great Proletarian Cultural Revolution (GPCR), was a mass campaign initiated by the central leadership of the CCP and left factions. It aimed to restore the proletarian (and therefore socialist) line within the Communist Party by calling for grassroots movements around the country, while also working to create Maoist mass organizations that would replace the structure of the CCP

In the cities, workers were called to challenge their bosses, including bureaucrats and people supporting individualistic capitalist thinking within the Party and industry. Their actions didn't really involve large-scale strikes and unionizing efforts as much as it did the critiquing of bureaucratic formations in their local governments, workplaces, and especially within the Party itself. They also pushed for the enforcement of policies like the Iron Rice Bowl, which guaranteed workers lifetime employment and benefits from the state. Workers were also heavily involved in local movements and debates regarding the direction of the country and how their local communities can play a part in them, and many joined the Red Guards to engage in the ideological struggle within the party.

Author: stayflyyyy
Content: Peasants in the countryside, who had suffered under the centuries long Chinese feudalism and Western colonialism, were organized into democratic assemblies and councils. These groups were sometimes supported by Red Guards, continued the land reform efforts that had begun in the 1950s. Although most of the land had already been redistributed by that point, the GPCR aimed to confront any resurgence of landlordism, often promoted by wealthy farmers. Peasants reclaimed land and fought against remnants of feudal thinking that justified the existence of landlords and social hierarchies. A big part of this struggle was also the confrontation towards Confucianism, which had historically justified the hierarchical feudal order. Confucian values like ‚Äúpeace and harmony‚Äù were direct justifications of wealthy farmers to keep their regressive traditions and lands. One very visible part of this struggle against old ideas was the struggle against patriarchal traditions, like foot binding, which symbolized the binding of women to the husband and to the land. Women played a huge active role in the cultural revolution, which necessitated confrontation against feudalist gendered structures and deeply ingrained chauvinistic thinking.

Author: stayflyyyy
Content:
In both large cities and small towns, high school and university students organized and fought against bureaucratic social structures and intellectual elitism within their campuses and in their communities. Many of them joined the Red Guards, where they took part in mass debates on how their communities and schools should be organized. Scientific reform of education was a big part of this struggle, as the focus shifted toward scientific thinking and the elimination of old superstitions and feudal beliefs. These efforts contributed to a large explosion of literacy and the eventual widespread standardization of simplified Chinese in 1977. By 1978, primary school attendance was universal across China, and the country was then able to focus more on building up its education system across all levels, as the struggle to literacize the Chinese masses was largely completed during the GPCR.

The three primary groups: workers, peasants, and students, were the largest participants in the GPCR, and their efforts in opposing feudal traditions, challenging bureaucracy, and promoting mass organization were central to directing the policy of the nation during and after the GPCR. China would not be where it is today without the GPCR, because it was the Cultural Revolution that eliminated unscientific thinking in the countryside and in the cities through genuine countrywide mass movements.

Author: stayflyyyy
Content: Marx because he was the theoretical leader of the scientific communist movement, Lenin because he developed Marxism to the point of DotP and of the first analysis of imperialism and socialism on a global scale, and Mao because he developed a method of revolution in the colonial countries whereas Lenin's analysis of imperialism was restricted to imperialist competiton and its function within the capitalist countries, Mao's analysis of imperialism was from the perspective of the colonized people, and his developments of PPW and New Democracy aided that struggle

Author: stayflyyyy
Content: this is not mentioning their other advancements on Marxism as a science, like Marx's formation of historical materialism and thee various concepts written in Das Kapital, or Lenin on the state, democratic centralism, and DotP, or Mao's discovery of the Mass Line, and development of the two line struggle

Author: omnomswag
Content: if a mere peanut were encapsulated in a giant metallic iron dome of sorts spanning roughly the same diameter of our earth, by the time the peanut has reach the other side of the dome from within and then back, that would still constituent as an insufficient amount of time to properly digest and praise the foundational layouts set by marx and engels and later expanded and qualitatively added upon by lenin. on the other hand however Mao's contributions to the wider movement and overall development of communism has been minimal at best. Mao didn't invented the 'mass line' strategy or even was the first to execute it with such precision and with tremendous results. to claim the mass line is as maoist as the mao suit, its just that, it's not. communist movements and leaders from all parts of the world have stressed cooperation with the masses, using their pool of knowledge to better THEIR lives, we dont even have to go any further than the bolsheviks, for how supposedly bureaucratic they are deemed by falsifiers and revisionists of the likes, you can't take away that even the bolsheviks have executed the mass line strategy when it came to propaganda and the consolidation of party power. going over protracted people's war, one simple rebuttal, it is not and it will never be universally applicable. if it were we would have seen similar revolutions following the ppw strategy succeed in far more peasant dominated countries in colonized regions but yet nothing of meaningful results has ever came out of it. as opposed to Lenins vanguard party model which has succeeded again and again and again in places with vastly different histories and colonial conditions. why lenin is more influential and substantive than mao? mao copied lenins NEP, appropriated common marxist values like the aforementioned mass line as his own, and at that could not even sustain a world wide revolution.

Author: kaviarormonroe
Content:
Syndicalism relies on the same principle that the bourgeoisie rely on to keep their power, that is inviting the majority to choose their government, a sufficient enough proof of the reactionary character of syndicalism is that right-wing deviationists and reactionary economist have always proposed unionism in opposition to the total class rule of the proletariat (ex. Mussolini). 
Unions limit the action of the proletariat to economical reforms, the bourgeoisie today already cling to supporting unions, because they deprive the proletariat of political power. 
The unions limit proletarian consciousness to the subject of "trade" only, keeping the bourgeoisie happy in their position of political power and dominance over the means of production, whereas the class Party seizes all the political power from the bourgeoisie and as a result can actually exercise control over the means of production and pursue political power to actually change the status-quo.

Author: kaviarormonroe
Content:
Don't get me started on Anarcho syndicalism
> The weakness of anarcho-syndicalism, even in its classic period, was the absence of a correct theoretical foundation, and, as a result a wrong understanding of the nature of the state and its role in the class struggle; an incomplete, not fully developed and, consequently, a wrong conception of the role of the revolutionary minority, that is, the party. Thence the mistakes in tactics, such as the fetishism of the general strike, the ignoring of the connection between the uprising and the seizure of power, etc.

Author: kaviarormonroe

Author: kaviarormonroe
Content:
The problem is that feminism posits patriarchy as the** primary and most enduring axis of social domination**, situating male supremacy as a historically autonomous system of oppression (You've seen how my argument with Mathilde shows this clearly). Such a formulation mystifies the actual social totality‚ÄîWhich is, duh, the capitalist mode of production‚Äîand dislocates the real source of women‚Äôs oppression from the objective conditions of class society to the sphere of biologized and moralistic antagonisms. In so doing, feminism becomes not a negation of capital, but a supplementary ideology within its reproductive cycle.

Radical feminism imagines patriarchy as a transhistorical structure, either predating (something that radfems really really like to say because they dont understand the point) or functioning alongside capitalism as an independent system. This view is incompatible with the historical materialist method as for Marxists, oppression cannot be abstracted from the social relations of production. 

The subjugation of women is not a parallel system but a moment within the dialectic of capital accumulation. Capital subsumes the reproductive function of the family, weaponizing gendered roles not out of male desire, but out of economic necessity. The family form under capitalism is a productive institution for the reproduction of labour power‚Äînot merely a site of male power.
(Read origins of the family by engels)

Radical feminism thus reifies gender into an abstract and autonomous antagonism, detaching it from its basis in the commodity form. This detachment serves bourgeois ideology by displacing class as the principal contradiction and replacing it with an eternal moral struggle between the sexes.

The radical feminists valorizes identity, constructing womanhood as an invariant subject of political truth. Yet, the invocation of woman as a political identity is itself a regression. 
(nobody tell these feminists that sex is also an identity lol. And that if you‚Äôre claiming oppression is on the basis of binary sex characteristics you‚Äôre basically just reinventing gender with different more rigid rules)

 It affirms the legitimacy of bourgeois subject-formation even as it claims to resist it.
The state cannot liberate women any more than it can liberate the proletariat; it exists to reproduce the wage relation, the family, and private property.

To tie women‚Äôs liberation to state power is to conscript feminist struggle into the reproduction¬†of¬†capital.

Author: kaviarormonroe
Content:
> ...the real problem is not to penetrate the 'hidden kernel' of the commodity - the determination of its value of the work consumed in its production - but to explain why work assumed the form of value of a commodity, why it can affirm its social character only in the commodity-form of its product.
>  *The Sublime Object of Ideology, Slavoj zizek*

> In the materialist method philosophical sophistry and disputations around abstract concepts are replaced by the study of the real world... The statement ‚ÄúMan proposes, God disposes‚Äù is interpreted by the theologian from the point of view of the omnipotence of God. The materialist searches for the cause of the discrepancy between expectations and results, and finds it in the social effects of commodity exchange and competition. The politician debates the desirability of freedom and of socialism; the materialist asks: from what individuals or classes do these demands spring, what specific content do they have, and to what social need do they correspond? The philosopher, in abstract speculations about the essence of time, seeks to establish whether or not absolute time exists. The materialist compares clocks to see whether simultaneousness or succession of two phenomena can be established unmistakably.
> *Lenin as Philosopher, Anton Pannekoek*

Author: omnomswag
Content: Before you can understand Marxism in the russian context you need to be well acquainted w the russian condition itself

Author: omnomswag
Content:
Marxism was imported into russia from western europe during a time when the theories espoused by marx mainly referred to the Western european conditions. The crowning of gaul, he says (in reference to France being the catapult for revolutionary projectiles). 

You have to understand that the theories of marx at this time was supplemented by other works, mostly philosophical and epistemological ones, the philosophical and epistemological underpinnings of marx's work hasn't yet been fully realized (partly due to a lack of available sources of his own works, which havent yet been published, combined that w the general development of both the intellegentsia and working class), even in the realm of germany, nevertheless the backwards russia. Now in the russian context the supplementation of marx can be divided into two major currents, that at most times complimented eachother, that of the kantian appendix and the positivists reconciliation (mach, avenarius). This supplement was due (in russia) because marx's theory was in large seen as a theory of economics (not that different from political economic theories in the west) This drove marxism in the russian context into taking the place of liberalism in russia. a scientific, economic determinist theory, not the natural and social science that in its matured form by marx, engels, and dietzgen is supposed to be. The russian marxism is a major and flawed interpretation, coupled w actually existing socialist movements that of narodism, which in all fairness represented marxism better than actual russian marxism. This marxism was not a revolutionary theory, it is simply an economic law which does not violate capital.

Author: omnomswag
Content: Marxism never became a revolutionary guide that can and should have superseded the russian condition, by lenins own theoretical hands it became a servant of the russian condition. This marxism is a few building blocks away from the liberalism of western europe. Not a theory of proletarian struggle which has the unique ability to forever enriched itself, but a stagnant slave to preesxiting social relations.
